    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "5e3183a21d58c7e6",
      "text": "> Alain Badiou worked for about fifteen years on \"Logics of the Worlds,\" the sequel to his great work \"Being and the Event\" (published in 1988, by diaphanes in 2005). But what does continuation mean? In 1988, the ontological concern was to prove, based on mathematics, that being, conceived as such, is only indifferent manifoldness. The following problem then arises: How is it to be understood against the background of this indifference that truths not only exist, but that they also appear in certain worlds? What is the visible or objective body of a truth? It cannot be deduced from ontology. Rather, a logic of appearance, a phenomenology, must be constructed. This is precisely what the present book aims at: a \"Great Logic\" which, giving an account of the order of worlds, authorizes the thinking of truths as exceptions to that order. Contemporary materialism holds that there are only bodies and languages. The materialistic dialectic, which is worked out here to the smallest detail, asserts against it: Yes, there are only bodies and languages except that there are truths. Only in the sign of this \"except that\" a life is still possible, which would not be unworthy. A life in which the democratic individual incorporates itself into that transgression of its own existence which is called subject."
