        "text": "Let's take another leap, this time to Warsaw of 1920, where the logician Jan Łukasiewicz is working. Logic is undergoing the most revolutionary changes since Aristotle, after mathematical techniques are applied to it for the first time. Gottlob Frege and Bertrand Russell, a German and an English logician, have just invented a new mathematical logic, which today is called - somewhat misleadingly - classical logic. Although this logic is a radical new development, it nevertheless adheres to the orthodoxy of the theorem of excluded thirds and the theorem of excluded contradiction. Accordingly, propositional sentences in this new logic have one of the two \"truth values\" (as logicians call them):w (true and only true) and f (false and only false). Łukasiewicz ponders whether there could be more than two, and thus invents multivalued logic - that is, logics in which there are more than two truth values."
