        "text": "[[Graham Priest]], Gibt es mehr als nur wahr oder falsch?\n\nLet's take another leap, this time to Warsaw of 1920, where the logician Jan Łukasiewicz is working. Logic is undergoing the most revolutionary changes since Aristotle, after mathematical techniques are applied to it for the first time. Gottlob Frege and Bertrand Russell, a German and an English logician, have just invented a new mathematical logic, which today is called - somewhat misleadingly - classical logic. Although this logic is a radical new development, it nevertheless adheres to the orthodoxy of the theorem of excluded thirds and the theorem of excluded contradiction. Accordingly, propositional sentences in this new logic have one of the two \"truth values\" (as logicians call them):w (true and only true) and f (false and only false). Łukasiewicz ponders whether there could be more than two, and thus invents multivalued logic - that is, logics in which there are more than two truth values.\n\n[…]\n\nLet us now set the clock back to a time in the 1st or 2nd century before our era. We are somewhere in India. Nāgārjuna, the philosophical founder of all Mahāyāna Buddhisms (of which there are many), writes his canonical text, Mūlamadhyamakakārikā (\"Fundamental Verses on the Middle Way\"). The Catu ̇sko ̇ti plays a central role in Nāgārjuna's analysis, but he gives it a surprising twist. In all Buddhist schools, a distinction is made between the conventional reality of our experience and that ultimate reality which is not veiled by our conceptual constructions. And according to Nāgārjuna, the ultimate reality is ineffable. (Remember that the Buddha refused to answer certain questions?) So there seems to be a fifth possibility beyond the four of the Catu ̇sko ̇ti: Unsayability.\nWe can easily add a fifth value to the FDE logic. Let us call this value l (for emptiness-emptiness, śūnyata, often used in Mahāyāna philosophy as a name for ultimate reality); l is the value of propositions that are unsayable-or better, of propositions that describe unsayable states; propositions themselves cannot be unsayable! Our five values now look like in the second small figure (see below right)."
